PY  - 2008
Y1  - 2008/11/01
DO  - 10.1162/qjec.2008.123.4.1329
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 123
IS  - 4
SP  - 1329
EP  - 1372
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We use randomized grants to generate shocks to capital stock for a set of Sri Lankan microenterprises. We find the average real return to capital in these enterprises is 4.6%–5.3% per year), substantially higher than market interest rates. We then examine the heterogeneity of treatment effects. Returns are found to vary with entrepreneurial ability and with household wealth, but not to vary with measures of risk aversion or uncertainty. Treatment impacts are also significantly larger for enterprises owned by males; indeed, we find no positive return in enterprises owned by females.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/qjec.2008.123.4.1329
ER  - 



